        <exploration>
            <title>A Dilation Not Centered at the Origin</title>
            <introduction>
                <p>
                    The center of a dilation does not have to be the origin,
                    <m>(0,0)</m>. It could be any point in the plane.
                </p>
            </introduction>
            <task>
                <introduction>
                    <p>
                        Use the GeoGebra applet <xref ref="fig-GGapp-new-center"/>
                        or a paper copy to complete the following. You will need 
                        to plot each point individually.
                    </p>
                    <figure xml:id="fig-GGapp-new-center">
                        <caption>GeoGebra applet for dilating triangle <m>\Delta EFG</m></caption>
                        <interactive xml:id="scale-not-origin"
                        platform="geogebra">
                        <slate surface="geogebra" material="uwqquwpn"/>
                        </interactive>
                    </figure>
                </introduction>
                <task>
                    <statement>
                        <p>
                            Sketch or construct the dilation of triangle <m>\Delta EFG</m>
                            with center <m>H</m> and scale factor <m>3</m>.
                        </p>
                    </statement>
                    <hint>
                        <p>
                            You can avoid using the Pythagorean Theorem by 
                            thinking of sides and diagonals of blocks on the 
                            grid as units; for example <m>HF</m> is equal to 
                            the diagonal of a <m>2\times 4</m>-rectangle 
                            so <m>HF'</m> should be equal to three of these 
                            diagonals.
                        </p>
                    </hint>
                    <answer>
                        <p>
                            The coordinates are as follows: <m>E'(12,4)</m>,
                            <m>F'(0,-8)</m>, and <m>G'(0,-2)</m>.
                        </p>
                    </answer>
                </task>
                <task>
                    <statement>
                        <p>
                            Sketch or construct the dilation of triangle <m>\Delta EFG</m>
                            with center <m>H</m> and scale factor <m>\frac{3}{2}</m>.
                        </p>
                    </statement>
                    <answer>
                        <p>
                            The coordinates are as follows: <m>E'(3,4)</m>,
                            <m>F'(-3,-2)</m>, and <m>G'(-3,1)</m>.
                        </p>
                    </answer>
                </task>
                <task>
                    <statement>
                        <p>
                                Sketch or construct the dilation of triangle <m>\Delta EFG</m>
                                with center <m>H</m> and scale factor <m>\frac{1}{2}</m>.                            
                        </p>
                    </statement>
                    <answer>
                        <p>
                            The coordinates are as follows: <m>E'(-3,4)</m>,
                            <m>F'(-5,2)</m>, and <m>G'(-5,3)</m>.
                        </p>
                    </answer>
                </task>    
            </task>
        </exploration>
</subsection>
<subsection xml:id="subsec-dilate-similartri-example">
    <title>Similar Triangles and Dilations</title>
    <p>
        We have observed that a dilation maps each figure onto a figure that
        has the same shape as the original, but the size is not preserved.
        When two figures have the same shape we say that the figures are 
        <term>similar</term>. Corresponding angles will be congruent and lengths of 
        corresponding sides will be proportional. We give a formal definition 
        for <term>similar triangles</term> but note that this definition can easily be 
        generalized for polygons with more than three sides.
    </p>
    <definition xml:id="def-similar-triangles">
        <statement>
            <idx><h>similar</h></idx>
            <idx><h>triangles</h><h>similar</h></idx>
            <p>
                Two triangles <m>\Delta ABC</m> and <m>\Delta DEF</m> are 
                said to be <xref ref="def-similar" text="custom">similar</xref> triangles
                if the following hold:
                <ul> 
                    <li>
                        <m>\Delta ABC</m> and <m>\Delta DEF</m> have three pairs 
                        of congruent corresponding angles 
                        <me>\angle A\cong\angle D, \angle B\cong \angle E, 
                        \angle C\cong \angle F</me>
                    </li>
                    <li>
                        and the ratios of the three pairs of corresponding 
                        sides are equal 
                        <me>\frac{DE}{AB}=\frac{EF}{BC}=\frac{FD}{CA}</me>.  
                    </li>
                </ul>
            </p>
            <p>
               We use the symbol <m>\sim</m> to denote similar figures. Thus,
               <m>\Delta ABC\sim\Delta DEF</m> means that <m>\Delta ABC</m> and 
               <m>\Delta DEF</m> are similar triangles.
                <notation>
                    <usage><m>\sim</m></usage>
                    <description>similar</description>
                </notation>
            </p>
        </statement>
    </definition>
    <p>
        In <xref ref="explor-nested-simtri"/>, we consider a situation in 
        which a vertex of a figure is mapped to itself by a dilation. As you
        complete this activity, look for relationships between similarity  
        and dilation.
    </p>
    <exploration xml:id="explor-nested-simtri">
        <title>Properties of a Dilation</title>
        <introduction>
            <p>
                In <xref ref="fig-nested-simtri"/>, a dilation takes 
                <m>\angle ABC</m> to <m>\angle DEC</m>.
            </p>
            <figure xml:id="fig-nested-simtri">
                <caption>GeoGebra applet for <xref ref="explor-nested-simtri"/></caption>
                <interactive xml:id="GGapp-nested-simtri" platform="geogebra">
                    <slate surface="geogebra" material="enwtc22h"/>
                </interactive>
            </figure>
        </introduction>
        <task>
            <statement>
                <p>
                    What is the center of the dilation? How do you know?
                </p>
            </statement>
        </task>
        <task>
            <statement>
                <p>
                    What is the scale factor of this dilation? 
                </p>
            </statement>
        </task>
        <task>
            <statement>
                <p>
                    Compute each of the ratios:
                    <ol>
                        <li>
                            <m>\frac{DE}{AB}</m>
                        </li>
                        <li>
                            <m>\frac{EC}{BC}</m>
                        </li>
                        <li>
                            <m>\frac{CD}{CA}</m>
                        </li> 
                    </ol>
                    What do you notice?
                </p>
            </statement>
        </task>
        <task>
            <statement>
                <p>
                    Compute the ratios:
                    <ol>
                        <li>
                            <m>\frac{DE}{BC}</m>
                        </li>
                        <li>
                            <m>\frac{EC}{AC}</m>
                        </li>
                        <li>
                            <m>\frac{CD}{AB}</m>
                        </li>
                    </ol>
                    Are these the same? Why or why not?
                </p>
            </statement>
        </task>
        <task>
            <statement>
                <p>
                    Are any of the angles in triangle <m>\Delta ABC</m> congruent 
                    to an angle in <m>\Delta DEC</m>? Identify all pairs of congruent
                    angles.
                </p>
            </statement>
        </task>
        <task>
            <statement>
                <p>
                    In <xref ref="fig-nested-simtri"/>, are triangles <m>\Delta ABC</m> and 
                    <m>\Delta DEC</m> 
                    <xref ref="def-congruent-polygon" text="custom">congruent</xref>? Explain.
                </p>
            </statement>
            <answer>
                <p>
                    No.
                </p>
            </answer>
        </task>
        <task xml:id="task-explor-nested-simtri-defsimilar">
            <statement>
                <p>
                    Are the triangles in <xref ref="fig-nested-simtri"/> similar? Explain.
                </p>
            </statement>
            <answer>
                <p>
                    Yes.
                </p>
            </answer>
        </task>
    </exploration>
